At the risk of stating the obvious, aircraft depend on lift from the wings 
to stay airborne. Lift is 'roughly' perpendicular to the wings...as soon as 
the aircraft, and its wings, rotate, the lift will be in the direction 
(roughly) perpendicular to the aircraft's roll, and consequently, NOT 
upwards. That's why when planes roll they look like they are doing a big 
corkscrew through the air, and in this case, the radius of that jumbo's 
corkscrew would have put it well below the deck...with no survivors :/﻿

Seriously, if an airliner were flying at that super slow speed, it wouldn't 
even be generating enough lift to stay in the air. If you watch the moment 
it passes the camera, you can see that a car driving at freeway speeds is 
even faster than that.

 Furthermore, the altitude that it would drop from rolling inverted would 
be quite significant because of the very slow roll rate and because lift is 
only generated in the direction of a vector going from the bottom of the 
lift surface to the to of the lift surface (the wings, in other words). So 
while an aircraft is upside down, it actually would be pulled towards the 
ground. In a lightweight fighter jet, it could roll inverted, then complete 
the roll 360 degrees in one second, so it would not experience much 
altitude loss, but not in an aircraft like this.﻿
